[2] Lithuania
Date: Wed 6 Aug 2014
Source: The Baltic Times [edited]
http://www.baltictimes.com/news/articles/35277/


One more case of African swine fever (ASF) has been detected in Lithuania.

The virus, which causes mass death rates in pigs, was found in a farmstead in the Utena district, the Ministry of Agriculture said on Wednesday [6 Aug 2014].

According to the Ministry, the farmer's pigs were treated with antibiotics but later died due to the disease. It has been confirmed the pigs suffered a case of African swine fever.

Currently, veterinary specialists are counting pigs and taking samples for laboratory tests within a radius of 3 and 10 km. Having received the results of the tests, farmers will be recommended to slaughter pigs.

African swine fever was detected on one of Lithuania's largest pig farms last month [July 2014], sparking mass death rates in pigs. A state of emergency was declared in large areas of the country to prevent the spread of the outbreak.

Polish and Baltic officials have also drawn up plans to combat the spread of the disease.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Lithuania submitted its follow-up report No. 2 on ASF on Wed 6 Aug 2014. The report, reporting the case above on a farm in Tauragnu parish, UTENA, is described as follows ("Affected population"):

"A dead pig (a 5-month-old male showing clinical signs similar to African swine fever) was delivered on 5 Aug 2014 to the National Food and Veterinary Risk Assessment Institute (NFVRAI) from a backyard farm (with 2 pigs). The pig had started to be sick on 29 Jul 2014 and died late night on 4 Aug [2014]. The other pig (a 5-month-old female) was clinically healthy. The State Food and Veterinary Service was immediately informed about this case, and samples from the dead pig and blood samples from the clinically healthy pig were taken for PCR and ELISA. On 6 Aug 2014, the NFVRAI confirmed African swine fever using real-time PCR and found positive results to African swine fever antibodies using ELISA. The other pig (the 5-month-old female) tested negative by PCR and ELISA. The clinically healthy pig was killed and destroyed."

The full report, including an interactive map, is available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=15789. - Mod.AS]

