[5] Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia and Poland: cooperative prevention/control effort
Date: Wed 6 Aug 2014
Source: The Pig Site [edited]
http://www.thepigsite.com/swinenews/37341/poland-baltics-agree-measures-to-combat-asf


EU Officials from the Baltic states and Poland have agreed on measures to combat the spread of the deadly African swine fever (ASF).

Swine fever was discovered on one of Lithuania's largest pig farms this month [August 2014], causing mass death rates in pigs. Fears that the disease could spread to other farms in the Baltics and Poland have been raised, reports The Baltic Times.

Now, a Baltic-Polish task force of food and veterinary service specialists from the 4 countries will be set up to combat the spread of the disease. Agriculture ministers of Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia and Poland agreed to the plans after a meeting.

Latvian Agriculture Minister Janis Duklavs said: "A common position is necessary in our talks with the European Commission for co-financing to help combat the spread of the disease as well as for compensation and other support mechanisms."

Close cooperation between the Baltics and Poland is needed also to implement prevention measures throughout the region and to make sure this is coordinated at a high level, the minister added.

African swine fever in Lithuania and Poland was discovered for the 1st time at the beginning of this year [2014]. The swine fever was 1st confirmed in Latvia on 26 Jun 2014.

A week later, Saema declared a state of emergency from 2 Jul until 1 Oct 2014 in dozens of counties in Latvia.

